When an  Object Schema Manager user tries to assign a role to a Jira user or a group, we see the below error

{code}
The Jira server was contacted but has returned an error response. We are unsure of the result of this operation. "
{code}

In order to change the global insight permissions you need to have the global permission of a JIRA Administrator, however, the Object Schema Manager should be able to assign roles within the Object schema

h3. Issue Summary

The Date Time Picker Custom Field remains flickering when the user tries to set the time on a Request in the Customer Portal when the language is German and Dutch. Check the [^Jira German Custom Field issue (Date Time Picker).mov]

(!) *T**his affects all the versions till 4.16.* 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a *JSM Service Desk Project* <ProjetcName>;
 # Create a *Date Time Picker Custom Field*;
 # Add the *Date Time Picker Custom Field* to the <ProjectName> *Screen*;
 # Go to <ProjectName>;
 # *Project Settings*;
 # *Request types*;
 # Create a *Request type*;
 # *Edit fields*;
 # *Add a field*;
 # *Date Time Picker*;
 # Go to the *Customer Portal*;
 # Click on the Avatar icon and select *Profile*;
 # *Edit your profile*;
 # Change the language to *Deutsch* or *Dutch* and click *save*;
 # Click on *Hilfecenter* next to your avatar;
 # Open a *Request* using the one you have created;
 # Click on the *calendar* icon;
 # Hover the mouse over the time section and trying to set it and watch it happen;

h3. Expected Results

To be able to set the time and date normally.
h3. Actual Results

The calendar remains flickering just like in the [^Jira German Custom Field issue (Date Time Picker).mov]
h3. Workaround

Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. 

The only thing is to be patient and try to slowly move the mouse pointer to the right place of the picker. 

This issue happens only when in the German Language and using this Date Time Custom Field. So, you can also avoid this by removing this field and using the Due To Time field instead.

h3. Issue Summary

REST user creation does not capture email-adress for the user attribute
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create an insight object type
 # Add an attribute that is of type 'User'
 # Do a post-query to <jira-baseurl>/rest/insight/1.0/object/create
 # In the query use a users email-adress for the user attribute

h3. Expected Results

The object is created and the Jira-user with the corresponding email-adress is stored in the user-attribute
h3. Actual Results

The query returns 
{code:json}
{
    "errorMessages": [],
    "errors": {
        "rlabs-insight-attribute-32": "User(s) (nic@ullman.com) not found in Jira"
    }
}{code}
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

We should make priority of clauses on IQL to minimize the CPU usage.

IQL:
{code:java}
object having inR() AND type = "Domain"
{code}
Should be in order:
{code:java}
type = "Domain" AND object having inR(){code}

h3. Issue Summary

When a company is migrating from another Asset Management tool (i.e. WASP) to Insight, it is not possible to use all existing asset barcodes (since Insight has its own QR Code). It demands changing the existing barcode tags from all assets.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Use another Asset Management tool;
 # Have tags with barcodes in all assets;
 # Start using Insight Asset Management;
 # Not possible to keep using the existing asset barcodes;

h3. Expected Results

Feature to allow to match the existing barcode (or upload the image).
h3. Actual Results

-
h3. Workaround

Relabel all assets with the new Insight QR Codes.
